---

# AGGREGATE FUNCTIONS

# COUNT()
Counts total rows.

```sql
SELECT COUNT(*) AS total_employees
FROM employees;
```

---

# SUM()
Calculates total value.

```sql
SELECT SUM(salary) AS total_salary
FROM employees;
```

---

# AVG()
Calculates average value.

```sql
SELECT AVG(salary) AS average_salary
FROM employees;
```

---

# MIN()
Finds smallest value.

```sql
SELECT MIN(salary) AS lowest_salary
FROM employees;
```

---

# MAX()
Finds largest value.

```sql
SELECT MAX(salary) AS highest_salary
FROM employees;
```

---

# STRING FUNCTIONS

# UPPER()
Converts text to uppercase.

```sql
SELECT UPPER(name)
FROM employees;
```

---

# LOWER()
Converts text to lowercase.

```sql
SELECT LOWER(name)
FROM employees;
```

---

# LENGTH()
Finds text length.

```sql
SELECT LENGTH(name)
FROM employees;
```

---

# CONCAT()
Combines text.

```sql
SELECT CONCAT(name, ' - ', department)
FROM employees;
```

---

# SUBSTRING()
Extracts part of text.

```sql
SELECT SUBSTRING(name, 1, 3)
FROM employees;
```

---

# TRIM()
Removes extra spaces.

```sql
SELECT TRIM(name)
FROM employees;
```

---

# NUMERIC FUNCTIONS

# ROUND()
Rounds decimal numbers.

```sql
SELECT ROUND(salary, 0)
FROM employees;
```

---

# CEIL()
Rounds up.

```sql
SELECT CEIL(45000.25);
```

---

# FLOOR()
Rounds down.

```sql
SELECT FLOOR(45000.99);
```

---

# ABS()
Returns absolute value.

```sql
SELECT ABS(-500);
```

---

# MOD()
Returns remainder.

```sql
SELECT MOD(10, 3);
```

---

# DATE FUNCTIONS

# NOW()
Returns current date and time.

```sql
SELECT NOW();
```

---

# CURDATE()
Returns current date.

```sql
SELECT CURDATE();
```

---

# YEAR()
Extracts year.

```sql
SELECT YEAR(joining_date)
FROM employees;
```

---

# MONTH()
Extracts month.

```sql
SELECT MONTH(joining_date)
FROM employees;
```

---

# DATEDIFF()
Finds difference between dates.

```sql
SELECT DATEDIFF(CURDATE(), joining_date)
FROM employees;
```

---

# Combining Functions with Conditions

## Example:
```sql
SELECT AVG(salary)
FROM employees
WHERE department = 'IT';
```

---

# Using Functions with GROUP BY

```sql
SELECT department, COUNT(*) AS total
FROM employees
GROUP BY department;
```

---

# Real-World Examples

## Total Employees:
```sql
SELECT COUNT(*) FROM employees;
```

## Highest Salary:
```sql
SELECT MAX(salary) FROM employees;
```

## Average IT Salary:
```sql
SELECT AVG(salary)
FROM employees
WHERE department = 'IT';
```

## Employee Name in Uppercase:
```sql
SELECT UPPER(name)
FROM employees;
```

---

# Common Mistakes

## Mistake 1: Using Aggregate Without GROUP BY
Wrong when mixing grouped and non-grouped columns.

---

## Mistake 2: Confusing COUNT(*) with COUNT(column)
COUNT(*) counts all rows  
COUNT(column) ignores NULL values

---

## Mistake 3: Wrong String Position in SUBSTRING
```sql
SUBSTRING(name, start, length)
```

---

# Best Practices

## 1. Use Aliases
```sql
SELECT AVG(salary) AS average_salary
FROM employees;
```

---

## 2. Combine Functions with Filters
Makes reports more meaningful.

---

## 3. Use Proper Data Types
Date functions require DATE columns.

